USER GUIDE — Working with Your Current System

This is how your system behaves and how to safely extend it.

🧩 1. How dropdown values work (CRITICAL)

Your system has 3 layers:

Frontend → Backend → HubSpot
🔑 Rule
HubSpot is the source of truth for dropdown values
🧠 Example

Property:

n4f_touchpoint_type

HubSpot options:

Event booth meeting
Webinar
...
❗ IMPORTANT

This will FAIL:

"Event booth Meeting" ❌

This will WORK:

"Event booth meeting" ✅
✏️ 2. How to add a NEW dropdown value
Step 1 — HubSpot

Add value in property:

Settings → Properties → Touchpoint → Edit property
Step 2 — Backend (validator)

Add to:

VALID_*

Example:

VALID_EVENTS.push("New Event")

🔄 3. How updates work (NEW behavior)

Now your system is:

protocolId → touchpointId → update
First scan
→ CREATE contact
→ CREATE touchpoint
→ STORE protocol
Second sync (same item)
→ UPDATE touchpoint (no duplicate)
Requirement

Frontend must store:

touchpointId
protocolId
🗂️ 4. Your backend storage

Stored in:

/data/protocols.json
Structure
{
  "protocolId": "...",
  "touchpointId": "...",
  "contactId": "...",
  "payload": {...},
  "status": "synced"
}
Use cases
debugging
re-sync
audit trail
future analytics
🛠️ 5. How to debug issues
Case 1 — Touchpoint not created

Check:

🔵 Touchpoint attempt

If missing → mapper issue

Case 2 — Validation error

Look for:

INVALID_OPTION

→ always dropdown mismatch

Case 3 — Duplicate contact

Check:

email present?

If no → duplicate expected

⚠️ 6. Known limitations (current state)

You currently still have:

❌ No identity resolution
Same person without email → new contact
❌ Frontend controlled schema
protocolSchema still frontend-based
❌ No DB (JSON only)

Fine for now, but not scalable

🚀 7. Recommended workflow for events
Before event
Update:
contact lists (env)
company lists (env)
Check:
dropdown values
users list
During event
Scan → Review → Save → Queue → Sync
After event
Check:
protocols.json
Spot-check HubSpot:
contacts
touchpoints
🧠 8. Golden rules (very important)
1. Never guess dropdown values

Always copy from HubSpot

2. Always send protocolId

This is your:

single source of truth
3. Never break mapping layer

Keep backend mapping clean:

protocol → hubspot property
4. Prefer warnings over errors

Your system is now:

resilient > strict
